Coastal Towns

Ireland being a small island nation means it has many coastal towns, both historic and newly developed. All the major cities in Ireland are close to the sea. This section of the report will focus on the financial impact the 2008 recession had on smaller coastal towns, and how much they have recovered. The 40 towns were grouped by provence to see which area of the country faired best after the recession.

The barplot shows the decrease in property prices across the whole of Ireland. It is not until 2014/2015 that prices begin to increase. The house prices in Leinster and Munster towns rebound faster than those in Connacht and Ulster.

The line graph above shows the difference when coastal town house prices are broken up between new houses and second-hand houses. Both are at the lowest around 2012/2013. The second-hand prices are more steady in their decrease and eventual increase. The price of new houses is much more reactive. In the last 2 years, the cost of a new house in Leinster, Munster and Connacht has skyrocketd.
